Sure, here's an example of how to create an instance of a class in Java:

Let's say we have a class named "Person" with two instance variables - "name" and "age" - and a constructor that initializes these variables:
```arduino
public class Person {
    private String name;
    private int age;

    public Person(String name, int age) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
    }
}
```
To create an instance of this class, we can use the "new" keyword followed by the name of the class and its constructor, passing the required arguments to the constructor. For example:
```java
Person person1 = new Person("John Doe", 30);
```
This statement creates a new instance of the "Person" class and assigns it to a variable named "person1". The constructor is called with the arguments "John Doe" and 30, which are used to initialize the "name" and "age" instance variables of the object.

We can now use the instance methods and variables of this object to perform various operations, for example:
```csharp
System.out.println(person1.getName()); // prints "John Doe"
System.out.println(person1.getAge()); // prints "30"
```
Here, we are calling two instance methods "getName()" and "getAge()" to retrieve the values of the instance variables "name" and "age" of the object "person1".
